      "oneSentenceSummary": "Calvin University is the premier Reformed liberal arts institution, producing graduates shaped by a Kuyperian vision of faith active in every sphere of life — scholars, teachers, healthcare professionals, business leaders, and artists who understand their work as vocation rather than career.",
      "pipeline": "Education, ministry, business, healthcare, social work, sciences, engineering, arts — Calvin graduates enter every professional sector shaped by a Reformed theological tradition that takes the integration of faith and learning more seriously than almost any other Christian institution.",
      "hiddenPathway": "The Calvin ecosystem in Grand Rapids is the hidden pathway. West Michigan is the most densely Reformed community in America — Amway, Meijer, Steelcase, Gentex, Bissell, and dozens of major corporations were founded by or are led by Calvin graduates and Dutch Reformed families. The alumni network is concentrated in one of the wealthiest and most economically dynamic mid-sized metro areas in the country. The Calvin Center for Christian Scholarship produces the most rigorous faith-and-learning scholarship at any evangelical institution. The January Series — a two-week speaker series bringing world-class intellectuals, artists, and leaders to campus — is open to the Grand Rapids community and is culturally significant in the region.",
      "institutionalSecret": "",
      "theRoom": "3,700 students on a 400-acre wooded campus on the southeast side of Grand Rapids. The Reformed tradition at Calvin is the most theologically distinctive of any evangelical institution — it carries a worldview of cultural engagement (the Kuyperian sphere sovereignty tradition) that produces graduates who see every profession as a vocation rather than merely a job. The intellectual culture is serious and self-aware. Grand Rapids is 30 minutes from Lake Michigan and 2.5 hours from Chicago.",
      "lifestyle": "Residential Christian campus with Kuyperian intellectual tradition, strong community ties in West Michigan, and deep integration of faith across every academic discipline.",
